a5 Pace Sieg/Siegling, restore (alyo)k, because śewi is fem.! (MM)&lt;br&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Translation [[Ogihara 2009]]: 288-289:&lt;br&gt;
a1 in the case of fixing, it is Duṣkṛta, || If a woman knocks against the seat of a monk, or he [raises her up] by both ... ///&lt;br&gt;
a2 to him. His daughter sits on the knees, or a woman stumbles and falls down over him, (... all of these cases are without sin.) /// &lt;br&gt;
a3 SA. (named ...) has come to an end. || (A monk) says a lewd word concerning sexual pleasure to a woman ///&lt;br&gt;
a4 it is Sthūlātyaya to him. If he says with the syllable 'trā' in the shape, ... not ... ///&lt;br&gt;
a5 he says to her by another excuse 5 he informs her of his wish 6 he shows love to her 7 ... ///&lt;br&gt;
b1 it is ... || If a woman  says a lewd word in these eight ways, a monk ... ///&lt;br&gt;
b2 it is ... If he speaks the language of other country to her, (and) it is a lewd word to her, it is [without sin.] ///&lt;br&gt;
b3 The classifications of the commentary have come to an end. || || With the excited mind ///&lt;br&gt;
b4 if he says in this way, (it is) Sthūlātyaya. || 'Give that as alms.' if he says in this way, (it is) Sthūlātyaya. I, ... to the portion ///&lt;br&gt;
b5 if he says, (it is) Sthūlātyaya. || 'Place by ... in this way.' He says the speech concerning the intention, ... ///
&lt;/p&gt;</item>
